July 14=2C 2025

Question: You=E2=80=99ve written that the lack of warning on the flooding=
 was due partly to a very limited government in Kerr County and a warning=
 system. How do you fix this problem?

Response:
Since then=2C I have learned that there were warnings from the National We=
ather Service. San Antonio had issued a flood watch in the Hill Country (a=
nd elsewhere) on July 3 at 1:18 p.m. The National Water Center Area Hydrol=
ogic Discussion issued a considerable flood warning at 6:22 p.m. on July 3=
 for areas including the city of Kerrville. Both were sent as text message=
s to all cell phones in the area. It should be noted that a flash flood wa=
rning in the Hill Country is the same as a snow warning in Vermont in Dece=
mber. A flash flood indicates the rapidity of and not the depth of the wat=
er in low lying areas. Flash flooding in itself is not dangerous.

Then at 1:14 a.m. on July 4=2C a flash flood warning was issued with the t=
ag =E2=80=9Cconsiderable.=E2=80=9D (There are three levels of warning. The=
re is a warning with no level of impact=2C a warning tagged =E2=80=9Cconsi=
derable=E2=80=9D and one tagged =E2=80=9Ccatastrophic.=E2=80=9D) The warni=
ng was sent via text messages to enabled mobile devices=2C and also issued=
 on the radio. At about 4:35 a.m.=2C the Kerr County sheriff=E2=80=99s off=
ice sent a warning as the river was flooding at low level crossings. So th=
e first warning of a significant or considerable event was sent at 1:14 a.=
m. on July 4. Subsequent warnings upgraded it to an emergency for south Ke=
rr County at 4:03 a.m. and by 5:34 a.m.

So the flooding was forecast=2C and warnings were distributed the day befo=
re. During the night=2C the forecast elevated to levels called considerabl=
e but not catastrophic. Weather forecasting is a science=2C but determinin=
g the intensity of the weather is hard to do. In this sense the technology=
 did not fail=2C and warnings=2C particularly the =E2=80=9Cconsiderable=E2=
=80=9D warning=2C was in place.

But warnings have to be delivered and read. The problem is that because th=
e significance of the event did not emerge until after midnight=2C many pe=
ople were already asleep. So it cannot be said that warnings weren=E2=80=
=99t issued and upgraded enough for the recipients to be concerned. Howeve=
r=2C the problem with cell phone warnings is that cell phone connectivity=
 is not always reliable. Many people turn off their cell phones when they=
 go to sleep=2C while others leave them in another room. So even though th=
e warning was given and delivered=2C the critical warning=2C the one that=
 would alert others=2C was delivered by a means that was unreliable in the=
 idiosyncratic Hill County.

Some would argue that there should have been siren. The problem with siren=
s is that they tell you something is up but not what it is. It could be a=
 fire=2C a car wreck or a flood. Also=2C the audio range of a siren is abo=
ut two miles=2C and as distance grows=2C the sound declines. It is easy to=
 assume that a distant siren could be a police or fire engine rushing to a=
n emergency. It is very possible to sleep through a siren=2C or to confuse=
 its nature=2C and not know what the emergency is. The problem in my mind=
 was not so much the forecast=2C nor the lack of warning=2C but the fact t=
hat the method of warning depended on the recipient=E2=80=99s relationship=
 with cell phones. The other problem is that weather forecasting is able t=
o identify the weather in general but not specific to place nor to intensi=
ty. In these circumstances=2C the idea that there was no warning given was=
 not true. There was a rough warning but the reliability of the cell phone=
 varies by location and time of delivery. And the last is the limit of
technology.

Question: You write about geopolitical trends in many parts of the world t=
hat have over the years come true =E2=80=93 the Russians attacking Ukraine=
=2C China=E2=80=99s economic slowdown =E2=80=93 to name a couple. Why woul=
d someone so deep into analyzing and forecasting what happens in the world=
 want to distance himself from it by living in the Hill Country which is a=
lso so different from where you grew up in densely populated New York=E2=
=80=99s Bronx?

Response:

Growing up in the Bronx was the foundation of my aversion to people. Later=
=2C I was a professor for a couple of decades=2C which compounded that ave=
rsion; colleagues and students and my occasional forays in government ceme=
nted my desire to be alone. So I decided to continue my work in geopolitic=
s and intelligence by selling my analysis in the private sector. There wer=
e risks=2C but having grown up in the Bronx=2C my calculus of risk is diff=
erent than most. At least my customers can=E2=80=99t knife me. I have a wi=
fe who is a bigger risk taker than me and thought it was a great idea. Eve=
ryone else thought I was demented. My business demanded that I anticipate=
 what will happen in the world. My life in the Bronx gave me insight into=
 how nations behaved=2C while the beauty and quiet of the Hill Country fre=
ed me from the noise of the world. I travel to far corners of the world on=
 occasion and then come home to a place of serenity. Who could want more?=
 Hegel once wrote that if you look at the world rationally=2C the
world will show itself to you rationally=2C a mutual relationship. And her=
e I can be rational about the world.

