Question: We used to hear that there was a population explosion that would=
 cause devastation by the end of the 20th century. Now we hear there will=
 be a labor shortage due to the low birth rates and a decline in populatio=
n numbers.  China had a one child policy for years. How much should govern=
ments be involved in demographic issues and should we look to immigration=
 from over-populated countries to help solve America=E2=80=99s labor issue=
s?

Response:

I have several good jokes playing around in my head on government and the=
 birth rate but I will spare you them. On the serious side=2C the job of g=
overnments is to protect the national interest.  The problem of old age is=
 that the elderly are not productive on the whole but consume a great deal=
=2C particularly in the medical area. There is a national interest at this=
 point in maintaining productivity for as much of their lives as possible.=
 That is the problem of medical research. What governments can do is fund=
 and increase that research. On the other side of the equation=2C increasi=
ng the birth rate would be desirable (joke deleted)=2C and the government=
 could offer financial incentives for women having babies. But beyond that=
=2C the fact that balancing birth rates and life expectancy is in the nati=
on=E2=80=99s interest. The decline in the birth rate is rooted in the shif=
ting of cultural norms as to the role of women in society=2C along with th=
e financial realities of raising children.

So while governments=2C given their mission=2C have an interest in birth r=
ate=2C the government would have to redefine cultural norms=2C and that is=
 something they are bad at. So I think the government could be helpful on=
 one side of the equation but not the other. It should be added that the U=
nited States=2C as a rapidly growing economy=2C has frequently had the imp=
erative to expand its population=2C something that has historically been s=
olved by immigration =E2=80=93 no one but a Native Americans can claim not=
 to descend from or be migrants to the U.S. But migrants historically crea=
te social stresses while enhancing  the economy=2C so this has to be hande=
d flexibly and subtly=2C which is not a strong suit of governments. At the=
 same time=2C that is the historic solution to increase over time the work=
 force in America.

