<strong>Question:</strong><em>&nbsp;You=E2=80=99ve written that the lack of=
 warning on the flooding was due partly to a very limited government in Ker=
r County and no&nbsp;warning system. How do you fix this problem?</em></p>

<p style=3D"margin: 10px 0;padding: 0;mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-tex=
t-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #202020;font-fami=
ly: Helvetica;font-size: 16px;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;"><br>
<br>
<strong>Response: </strong></p>

<div>Since then, I have learned that there were warnings from the National =
Weather Service. San Antonio had issued a flood watch in the Hill Country (=
and elsewhere) on July 3 at 1:18 p.m. The National Water Center Area Hydrol=
ogic Discussion issued a considerable flood warning at 6:22 p.m. on July 3 =
for areas including the city of Kerrville. Both were sent as text messages =
to all cell phones in the area. It should&nbsp;be noted that a flash flood =
warning in the Hill Country is the same as a snow warning in Vermont in Dec=
ember. A flash flood indicates the rapidity of and not the depth of the wat=
er in low lying areas. Flash flooding in itself is not dangerous.<br>
<br>
Then at 1:14 a.m. on July 4, a flash flood warning was issued with the tag =
=E2=80=9Cconsiderable.=E2=80=9D (There are three levels of warning. There i=
s a warning with no level of impact, a warning tagged =E2=80=9Cconsiderable=
=E2=80=9D and one tagged =E2=80=9Ccatastrophic.=E2=80=9D) The warning was s=
ent via text messages to enabled mobile devices, and also issued on the rad=
io. At about 4:35 a.m., the Kerr County sheriff=E2=80=99s office sent a war=
ning as the river was flooding at low level crossings. So the first warning=
 of a significant or considerable event was sent at 1:14 a.m. on July 4. Su=
bsequent warnings upgraded it to an emergency for south Kerr County at 4:03=
 a.m. and by 5:34 a.m.&nbsp;a Flash Flood Emergency was sent out for the Gu=
adalupe River.<br>
<br>
So the flooding was forecast, and warnings were distributed the day before.=
 During the night, the forecast elevated to levels called considerable but =
not catastrophic. Weather forecasting is a science, but determining the int=
ensity of the weather is hard to do. In this sense the technology did not f=
ail, and warnings, particularly the =E2=80=9Cconsiderable=E2=80=9D warning,=
 was in place.<br>
<br>
But warnings have to be delivered and read. The problem is that because the=
 significance of the event did not emerge until after midnight, many people=
 were already asleep. So it cannot be said that warnings weren=E2=80=99t is=
sued and upgraded enough for the recipients to be concerned.&nbsp;However, =
the problem with cell phone warnings is that cell phone connectivity is not=
 always reliable. Many people turn off their cell phones when they go to sl=
eep, while others leave them in another room. So even though the warning wa=
s given and delivered, the critical warning, the one that would alert other=
s, was delivered by a means that was unreliable in the idiosyncratic Hill C=
ounty.<br>
<br>
Some would argue that there should have been siren. The problem with sirens=
 is that they tell you something is up but not what it is. It could be a fi=
re, a car wreck or a flood. Also, the audio range of a siren is about two m=
iles, and as distance grows, the sound declines. It is easy to assume that =
a distant siren could be a police or fire engine rushing to an emergency. I=
t is very possible to sleep through a siren, or to confuse its nature, and =
not know what the emergency is. The problem in my mind was not so much the =
forecast, nor the lack of warning, but the fact that the method of warning =
depended on the recipient=E2=80=99s relationship with cell phones. The othe=
r problem is that weather forecasting is able to identify the weather in ge=
neral but not specific to place nor to intensity. In these circumstances, t=
he idea that there was no warning given was not true. There was a rough war=
ning but the reliability of the cell phone varies by location and time of d=
elivery. And the last is the limit of technology.</div>

