<strong>Response:</strong><br>
<br>
Growing up in the Bronx was the foundation of my aversion to people. Later,=
 I was a professor for a couple of decades, which compounded that aversion;=
 colleagues and students and my occasional forays in government cemented my=
 desire to be alone. So I decided to continue my work in geopolitics and in=
telligence by selling my analysis in the private sector. There were risks, =
but having grown up in the Bronx, my calculus of risk is different than mos=
t. At least my customers can=E2=80=99t knife me. I have a wife who is a big=
ger risk taker than me and thought it was a great idea. Everyone else thoug=
ht I was demented. My business demanded that I anticipate what will happen =
